stylometry: The tradeoff to balance when deciding how much inventory to order involves the cost of holding inventory versus the probability of a stock out (where the company runs out of inventory). The estimated order quantity (EOQ) is determined to reduce the probability of a stock out. The higher the variance of demand for a product, the EOQ rises. It requires the average demand and average order rate + the average lead time. The desired service level (or ability for a company to manage demand of the product) also comes into play, because a higher desired service level requires increased safety stock/inventory on hand. EOQ equalizes the carrying and ordering costs to their most efficient values based on the inputs provided.
